==German==

===Etymology===
From {{inh|de|gmh|siher}}, from {{inh|de|goh|sihur}}, from {{inh|de|gmw-pro|*sikur}}, from {{der|de|la|sēcūrus||without care, secure}}. Cognate with English {{l|en|secure}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|de|/ˈzɪçər/}}
** {{IPA|de|[ˈzɪçɐ]}} {{q|standard}}
*** {{audio|de|De-sicher.ogg|audio (Germany)}}
** {{IPA|de|[ˈziça]|[ˈzija]}} {{q|Ruhrgebiet}}
** {{IPA|de|[ˈzɪɕɐ]|[ˈzɪʃɐ]|[ˈze-]}} {{q|central Germany}}
** {{IPA|de|[ˈsiçɐ]}} {{q|Austro-Bavarian}}
*** {{audio|de|De-at-sicher.ogg|audio (Austria)}}
** {{IPA|de|[ˈsiχər]}} {{q|Alemannic}}

===Adjective===
{{de-adj|er|sichersten}}

# [[safe]], [[secure]] {{gloss|not dangerous or in danger}}
# [[sure]], [[certain]] {{gloss|convinced}}
#: {{ux|de|Ich bin (mir) '''sicher''', dass es heute regnen wird.|I am '''sure''' that it will rain today.}}

====Usage notes====
* In the sense of “sure”, the word is often construed with a reflexive dative. There is little change in meaning, though this dative may slightly stress the personal conviction. The dative is particularly frequent when the following subclause is omitted: {{m|de||Er ist sich sicher.|t=He’s sure}}.

====Declension====
